Description: A Hanover, Md.-based provider of RF technology and communications systems services for sports television broadcasting
Headquarters Regions: Greater Baltimore-Maryland Area, East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: The genesis of Broadcast Sports, Inc. (BSI) started back in 1979 when John Porter, Peter Larsson and Dave Curtis, a group of engineers at the Seven Network in Australia, began to explore new applications for the emerging portable video transmitters being developed for electronic news gathering. Parlaying early success at getting live images off yachts in the Sydney to Hobart race, the idea emerged to apply the technology to auto racing. The challenges were substantial, but the successes were compelling enough to catch the eye of a CBS executive who saw it as a perfect fit for the emerging NASCAR series. After a number of years of traveling back and forth between Australia and the US, this renegade group of entrepreneurs saw the market potential for these new systems in the US, picked up stakes and established Broadcast Sports Technologies (BST) in 1983. Over the course of the next 25 years, BST secured the reputation as the "go-to" provider of wireless point of view systems. This attention and the growing contracts surrounding our technologies allowed the development of small, rugged and more highly customized systems.
Industry Groups: Consumer Electronics, Hardware, Information Technology, Media and Entertainment, Sports, Video

Description: Autotalky - For a More Social Car
Headquarters Regions: Greater Baltimore-Maryland Area, Washington DC Metro Area, East Coast
Full Description: In 2008 when gasoline hit a high of $4 per gallon,  programmers under ABRS Tech took the initiative to innovate ways in looking for ways for ways to increase MPG for their commute cars to dampen  the cost of travelling from home to work. Bern Mutia, with the help of Rama Bollu and Avery Keyes created the GreenFuelBooster, a Platinum-anode-based electrolysis device to generate hydrogen from water and improve fuel burn. As the project required engine data monitoring, a Java application was developed to monitor OBD2 parameters affecting fuel burn. Presently, this application has been developed to a full web-enabled platform to do predictive trend diagnostics in cars. It has opened the possibility of cars as social entities by allowing it to communicate back to their vehicle owners and their Trusted Mechanics. The car’s engine data is its digital signature. This vision has come true with the help of bluetooth-enabled OBD2 plugins and data loggers in smartphones. Cars can now be better understood which only a few years ago was only within the realm of auto mechanics. Their platform hopes to help the ordinary consumer to save money by prolonging the lifetime of cars and hopefully encourage them to be responsible stewards of the environment. With the quantification of self, the use of fuel in transportation, they hope their platform can help the community, families and individuals plan and build for a better future.
Founders: Arn Lou Mutia, Bern Rewel Mutia

Users are required to upload images of at least 2048x1536 resolution, otherwise larger prints will appear pixilated.Other companies in the digital print market are [CafePress](http://crunchbase.com/organization/cafepress), [Zazzle](http://crunchbase.com/organization/zazzle), [FatHead](http://fathead.com) and [Photoways](http://crunchbase.com/organization/photoways)(Europe).  Mark Seremet was formerly the CEO of [Spreadshirt](http://crunchbase.com/organization/spreadshirt), a custom T-shirt printing company.
Industry Groups: Content and Publishing, Media and Entertainment, Sales and Marketing

Description: Since 2011, BCB Property Management has maximized the value and quality of multifamily and mixed-use buildings throughout New York City.
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: BCB Property Management is a full service real estate company focused on managing and redeveloping multi-family buildings in New York City. BCB has a strong commitment to investments in emerging marketplaces and prides itself on a proactive and ethical approach to management. BCB Property Management is a value manager, ensuring the right decisions are made to achieve the goals of its investors and residents. The in-house team is comprised of experts in management, finance, and development. Headquartered on Madison Avenue, BCB looks for underperforming properties in some of Brooklyn and Manhattan’s trendiest neighborhoods, from well-established cultural centers in the East Village and Williamsburg to emerging residential and retail pockets in Bed-Stuy and Morningside Heights. With each project undertaken, BCB oversees the full lifecycle of the development as it progresses from acquisition to sale. Along the way, BCB implements cost-effective renovation strategies that enhance the aesthetic value and structural integrity of the building, manages turnover with tact and expertise, and positions the asset for sound returns on the open market. In just a short period, BCB Property Management has acquired, improved and sold more than 60 multifamily and mixed-use properties throughout Manhattan and Brooklyn, a figure that consists of 70+ commercial units, 1,000+ residential units and nearly one million square feet of total living and work space. Whether refinanced or sold, BCB anticipates a capital event on an asset within 18 to 24 months of the purchase. Past successes include the Barclays Center-adjacent Atlantic Gardens project, two mixed-use buildings on Havemeyer Street in South Williamsburg, and a newly renovated apartment building on Lorimer Sreet in East Williamsburg.

The rest of the team is made up of CNET veterans, including Jeff Gerstmann formerly of [Gamespot](/organization/gamespot).
